{
  "title": "Semantic Response Differentiation Exercises",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7eaa2a0a8009fbe3",
      "text": "We recommend that readers do at least one exercise a day that trains [[Physical Awareness]] of different effects of speech. Exercises of the following type have proven to be particularly suitable for this purpose:"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d6877c7e11c5328d",
      "text": "Sit in a comfortable position, take a \"glass of water\" between the different \"courses\" of a linguistic menu by rubbing and shaking your hands and face, and only then move on to the next course. First speak a sentence or a phrase several times and pay attention to your semantic reaction, which according to Korzybski consists of the totality of changes in your thinking, your feeling and your bodily sensations, which in turn are triggered by the linguistic stimulus. After the next \"glass of water\" you move on to the next course and now pay particular attention to the differences from the previous one (reaction differentiation). A suitable menu consists of two to five courses."
    },
